Library preparation is the name of the preprocessing step, which is done before it is sequenced with the current technologies. The first step to sequence DNA is to obtain the DNA, which is done by lysing the cells of interest, which disrupts the cell membrane and therefore spills all its contents. The then spilled DNA is fragmented into smaller pieces, by either restriction enzymes or sonication, to have a size of about between 200-800bp. These steps are not necessary when preparing sequencing of ctDNA, as discussed in [[#intro-sec:ctDNA|[intro-sec:ctDNA]]], as the DNA is unbound and already digested into short fragments. Once the DNA is ready, it is phosphoryelated and an A-tail is added, before the adapter complex is ligated. This enables the DNA to bind to the flow cell which is covered with the reverse complement of the adapter ([[#fig:libraryprep|[fig:libraryprep]]]).

