The addition of the ctDNA samples led to a further bipartition edge, which separates the “right liver lobe“, “small bowel“ and “right cerebral lobe“ lesions from the rest of the tree ([[#fig:phyloCA9ctDNA|[fig:phyloCA9ctDNA]]]). This was already inferable from the topology of the previous tree in [[#fig:tanglePhyloCA9|[fig:tanglePhyloCA9]]] “joint“, but is even more pronounced with the inclusion of the ctDNA samples.

This shows that the addition of more samples helps to refine and improve the trajectory and history of cancer samples and it is vital to do this analysis jointly to generate the optimal result.

